Pricing is very expensive and not always suitable for a family day/evening out.

My family and I found the Glasgow Airport is easily accessible when it comes to visual. It has clear signage and wayfinding. At times it could get really crowded and perhaps something could be done by airport management to improve the situation with the crowd and dissemination of information especially. Despite that we find in terms of accessibility it is well designed for.

I had an overall very good experience at Glasgow airport a couple of years ago. We had booked priority boarding as I am visually impaired, and this was all very well organised. We were allowed to skip long queues as well.

The revamped Glasgow Queen Street took a bit of getting used to for me as I’m very light sensitive and I find it bright. The layout is good and the the new ticket gates accept my blind persons travel card so I can go through the barriers unaided, saves me waiting for a member of staff, I didn’t know about the location of the disabled accessible toilet which is located on the main concourse level, I went down stairs with a family member and they saw the accessible one on our return.  The staff in this station are very helpful and will take you to the correct train if needed.  Platforms 8 and 9 are down stairs which is fine for me, however the lifts for these platforms are sometimes out of order and there is no alternative to my knowledge. I am a guide dog owner with both sight and hearing impairments

I haven't been in Glasgow Central since the Lock Downs.However, I always it very disorientating as there is such a wide space with no tactile help. I think there ought to be paths created by tactile tiles, such as there is in the airport for Rome.

Brussels, central station is relatively small, it is square shaped, the ticket sales is on one side, and you have markings on the floor, which is the only accessibility feature, apart from lifts, so that people in wheelchairs can go down to the platforms. It is very easy to locate platforms. The acoustics are find phone for hearing the announcements, but it is very echoey and when street musicians play it is very easy to get the orientated.

For me it is the most accessible station I have ever used.

Question 1_24_TEXT: Porte de Namur, Brussels / popular  metro station
Question 2: I find the station very inaccessible, without  any lines to follow with the cane, so that we don't know which direction we have to go when taking the metro. I have learned it, keeping in mind which side is the direction where I need to go, and counting steps. But stil, the entrance doors have no sinee what soever and I lose lots of time touching and feeling the details.  Fortunately,people are kind around here, and we basically rely on their help. Even the mobility instructor did not have any other solution then asking for help. The positive side however is that once we go out the stairs, there are some tactil round sines indicating that in front of us the metro will pass and we should not surpass them. They are quite obvious with the cane.
Very confusing system;
Not all tube stations in London are wheelchair friendly which makes the experience of visiting London a bit daunting.
